## Article Improvement Notes

### Critical-Rendering-Path.md
- `content-visibility: auto` — A powerful CSS property that lets the browser skip rendering off screen content. Very relevant to CRP optimization.

### CSS-CSSOM-and-DOM-Rendering-in-Browser.md
- Heavy overlap with CRP article — Consider adding a cross reference note at the top explaining how the two articles relate. CRP focuses on optimization; this one focuses on the rendering mechanics.
- `content-visibility` and CSS containment (`contain` property) — Modern browser rendering optimizations missing.

### css-js-ui-optimization.md
- `@import` vs `<link>` penalty — Not mentioned that `@import` in CSS creates sequential downloads.
- PurgeCSS and dead CSS elimination — Only mentioned in CRP article but not here where it fits naturally.

### image-optimization.md
- `fetchpriority` attribute — Mentioned briefly but not with a dedicated section. Very important for LCP.

### network-optimization.md
- HTTP/3 Server Push — States "Yes" for HTTP/3 Server Push. HTTP/3 does NOT support Server Push. Chrome removed support in Chrome 106. This should be corrected.
- 103 Early Hints — A new HTTP status code that allows servers to send preload and preconnect hints before the full response. Important for TTFB optimization.
- `stale-while-revalidate` directive — Mentioned in a table row but not explained with examples.

### video-optimization.md
- DASH (Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP) — HLS is covered but DASH is only mentioned in passing. Should at least note the difference.
- Intersection Observer for lazy video loading — Load video only when scrolled into view.
- `<video>` accessibility — Captions (`<track>`), `aria-label`, keyboard controls. Not mentioned at all.
- Video compression comparison table — File size savings per codec at equivalent quality.

